		<p>
			Creating a site that speaks to clients while educating and coaching at the same time is a difficult feat. I wanted the site to be easily accesible to anyone looking to fix a problem or looking into my company, so no jargon or confusing terms.
        </p>
        <p>
            I would be tasked with all facets of this project, copywriting, design, and developing. I wanted to stress speed in the website, a quick start up and download of the components. The design I wanted to be simple but with a bit of flare, to be eye-catching and rememberable.
		</p>
		<h3 class="subhead">Research</h3>
		<p>
			I poured over Dribbble and went through as many portfolio sites as I could, each being exceptionally different. Not finding a style that I thought I wanted my site to go in, I took different pieces of design techniques and incorporated them into my ideas.
		</p>
        <h4 class="subhead--sub">Layout</h4>
        <p>
            The layout of other sites is something that I was very aware of, there are a lot of one page sites and I wasn't sure if that was worth emulating. I wasn't sure if that would be viewed as easier for a potential client to navigate or would they mind go back and forth between different pages.
        </p>
        <h4 class="subhead--sub">Color Scheme</h4>
		<p>
			I've always used three colors as my color scheme and always wanted to do some kind of gradient. I decided early in the planning phase that I would have a gradient, well 3 actually and they would rotate on load. Similar to what I do on this site, since this one was created first. I took so long making this site, that gradients became fashionable and were being done well.
		</p>
        <h4 class="subhead--sub">Content</h4>
		<p>
			The most important part and what I spent most of my time doing. Looking up how other freelancers and small businesses write their content. How straightforward were they, "I make mobile apps", or vague "I'm a designer". I discounted "big name" freelancers since they're approach would be different then mine. They aren't building a name and needing to walk people through their work, I am. So, I just searched for local people or low-level good work people.
		</p>
